{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17529503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17529503"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:56:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:56:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14424"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14424","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14424"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.05,0.74,0.06,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7119"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59852"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7119","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7119"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14424"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45269"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3743"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16986"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17754"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59852","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59852"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of fatigue and generalised weakness. She has a medical history of rheumatoid arthritis diagnosed five years ago, for which she takes methotrexate and prednisolone. She does not take any other regular medications. On examination, she appears pale but otherwise well. Her vital signs are within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 98 g/L (115-165)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMean corpuscular volume (MCV): 88 fL (80-98)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 7.2 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeutrophils: 4.5 x 10^9/L (2.0-7.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets: 280 x 10^9/L (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EErythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR): 55 mm/hr (1-20)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EC-reactive protein (CRP): 32 mg/L (\u0026lt;5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFerritin: 390 \u00b5g/L (15-200)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum iron: 6 \u00b5mol/L (10-30)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETransferrin saturation: 15% (20-55)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Folate deficiency","Felty syndrome","Anaemia of chronic disease","Haemochromatosis","Iron deficiency anaemia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation and laboratory results are most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Eanaemia of chronic disease\u003C/strong\u003E. The key features supporting this diagnosis are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E1. Presence of a chronic inflammatory condition (rheumatoid arthritis)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E2. Mild normocytic anaemia (haemoglobin 98 g/L with MCV 88)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E3. Elevated inflammatory markers (erythrocyte sedimentation rate 55 mm/hr, C-reactive protein 32 mg/L)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E4. Low serum iron (6 \u00b5mol/L) and low transferrin saturation (15%)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E5. Elevated ferritin (390 \u00b5g/L)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn anaemia of chronic disease, inflammatory cytokines lead to increased hepcidin production, which reduces iron availability for erythropoiesis. This results in a functional iron deficiency despite adequate or elevated iron stores.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIron deficiency anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with low ferritin levels, which is not the case here. The elevated ferritin in this patient is likely due to the underlying inflammatory condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemochromatosis\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by iron overload, with elevated serum iron, transferrin saturation, and ferritin levels. This patient\u0027s low serum iron and transferrin saturation are inconsistent with haemochromatosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFelty syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a complication of long-standing rheumatoid arthritis characterised by neutropenia and splenomegaly. While this patient has rheumatoid arthritis, her neutrophil count is normal (4.5 x 10^9/L), and there is no mention of splenomegaly, making Felty syndrome unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFolate deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents with macrocytic anaemia and would not explain the abnormal iron studies seen in this case. Additionally, this deficiency typically does not cause elevated inflammatory markers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of anaemia of chronic disease primarily involves treating the underlying condition. In some cases, erythropoiesis-stimulating agents or intravenous iron may be considered, particularly if the anaemia is severe or significantly impacting the patient\u0027s quality of life.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Anaemia of chronic disease is characterised by low serum iron, low transferrin saturation, and elevated ferritin levels.","Elevated inflammatory markers (erythrocyte sedimentation rate, C-reactive protein) support the diagnosis of anaemia of chronic disease."],"references":["Weiss G, Ganz T, Goodnough LT. Anemia of inflammation. Blood. 2019;133(1):40-50. doi:10.1182/blood-2018-06-856500"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45269"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14424"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45269","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/45269"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-09T11:09:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-09T11:10:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7119"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59852"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3743","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3743"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Anaemia of chronic disease","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-09-23T21:59:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-23T21:59:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"2"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4965","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4965"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Haematological Presentations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:22:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-17T23:22:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"22"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4977","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4977"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Older Persons\u0027 Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:22:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-17T23:22:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"22"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11625","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11625"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Adult Internal Medicine (AIM)","synonyms":null,"